nks":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3078"},{"type":"tags","id":"3229"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9295"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77186"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old male patient presented to the neurology clinic with progressively worsening involuntary movements, personality changes, and coordination difficulties over the past 4 years, resulting in recurrent falls. The patient\u0027s wife reported a concomitant increase in irritability and mood swings over the past 3-4 years. Upon further inquiry, the patient\u0027s wife revealed that his late father also experienced similar symptoms. During examination, the patient exhibited brief, irregular, and jerky movements affecting his face, limbs, and trunk. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of gait would you expect in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Waddling Gait","Ataxic Gait","Festinating Gait","Choreiform Gait","Sensory Gait"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical scenario, the patient is presenting with characteristic signs and symptoms suggestive of Huntington\u0027s disease. These include involuntary movements (choreiform movements), personality changes, difficulty with coordination, and positive family history. The presence of choreiform movements, along with the patient\u0027s age of onset, supports the diagnosis of Huntington\u0027s disease. The type of gait seen in this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Echoreiform gait\u003C/strong\u003E, which is seen in disorders affecting the basal ganglia, including Sydenham\u0027s chorea, Huntington\u0027s Disease, etc and is characterized by irregular and unpredictable pattern characterized by involuntary and purposeless movements of the legs and feet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaddling gait\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by an exaggerated side-to-side movement of the hips while walking. It is often associated with weakness or dysfunction of the hip abductor muscles and can be seen in conditions such as muscular dystrophy, hip dysplasia, or myopathies. The gait appears as a swaying motion, resembling the waddling gait of a duck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtaxic gait\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly observed in cerebellar disorders and is described as a clumsy, staggering movement with a wide-based gait. The patients are usually not able to walk straight in a line from heel-to-toe and the patient\u0027s body may sway from side-to-side while they are standing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFestinating gait \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterized by progressively shorter and quicker steps and can also be accompanied by reduced arm swing and difficulty in initiating movements. It is usually seen in patients with Parkinson disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory gait\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as stomping gait is usually observed in patients with disorders of the dorsal column or peripheral nerves, it is a result of loss of proprioceptive input and the patient walks by slamming his foot on the ground in an attempt to know it\u0027s location.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Choreiform gait is seen in patients with Huntington\u0027s disease."],"references":["Stoker TB, Mason SL, Greenland JC, Holden ST, Santini H, Barker RA. Huntington\u0027s disease: diagnosis and management. Pract Neurol. 2022 Feb;22(1):32-41. doi: 10.1136/practneurol-2021-003074. Epub 2021 Aug 19. PMID: 34413240.","Martino D, Stamelou M, Bhatia KP. The differential diagnosis of Huntington\u0027s disease-like syndromes: \u0027red flags\u0027 for the clinician. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry. 2013 Jun;84(6):650-6. doi: 10.1136/jnnp-2012-302532. Epub 2012 Sep 19. PMID: 22993450; PMCID: PMC3646286.","Pyo SJ, Kim H, Kim IS, Park YM, Kim MJ, Lee HM, Koh SB. Quantitative Gait Analysis in Patients with Huntington\u0027s Disease. J Mov Disord. 2017 Sep;10(3):140-144. doi: 10.14802/jmd.17041. Epub 2017 Aug 31. PMID: 28851209; PMCID: PMC5615174."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62693"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13008"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62693"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:16:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T11:16:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77186"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"hea